[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/roman_keycard"]
[Student "S"]
{Partner's 3\D bid shows a very good hand with probable slam interest. It is very tempting to say 3NT now but you don't have \Hs stopped and don't know if partner does. So with good \D support you bid 4\D. Partner bids 4NT. What is your response? 

You have 2 Key-Cards, the \SA and \DK. But you don't have the \DQ so you answer 5\H. Partner bids 6\D.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "2"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "E:KT8.AK9864..AKQ7 Q974.T3.AQT7.T65 A652.QJ52.KJ3.82 J3.7.986542.J943"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1H pass 3H pass 4C pass 4H pass 4NT pass 5C pass 6H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 2, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "8d9425ae7f4c96934e9a559ec88143d92a379c5105e2df63239c928a88aae2c0"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/roman_keycard"]
[Student "S"]
{Your partner's 3\H is a limit-raise, 11-12 points with \H support.  

What you want to know is whether partner holds the \SA. If you bid 4NT and he shows two Key-Cards all will be well, you will know they are the two missing Aces. But if he shows just 1 Key-Card you will be in the soup since you can't tell if that Key-Card is the useful \SA or the practically useless \DA. So you don't use RKCB, you use control-showing and bid 4\C. Partner says 4\H.  

Partner would have control-bid \Ds if he had the Ace. You may not think that helps but it does since now you can bid RKCB. You bid 4NT and he answers 5\C. What is your next bid? 

It was a lot of work but you have figured out that partner holds 11-12 points including one Key-Card which must be the \SA. It looks like the slam is a good idea so you say 6\H.}

